WEBVTT

00:00:00.320 --> 00:00:06.320
Hi, thank you for joining me today. I really appreciate that. I'm a staff engineer at

00:00:06.320 --> 00:00:11.840
Appsilon, the company that brought you the Rhino framework for building Shiny applications.

00:00:12.560 --> 00:00:18.559
But today I want to share with you a story, a case study of a TARS application. I'm a delivery

00:00:18.559 --> 00:00:24.320
manager at that project and this is one of our most complex apps that we built together with

00:00:24.320 --> 00:00:32.799
one of the Hollywood film studios together. Let me start with the question, how does the

00:00:32.799 --> 00:00:39.360
film industry work? So on a basic level you might imagine that the most important part

00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:46.720
is someone in front of the camera, actor, actress, someone behind the director and they are shooting

00:00:46.720 --> 00:00:52.639
the scenes and this is the crucial part of the moviemaking process. It might look like this

00:00:53.599 --> 00:00:59.439
or like this, so there are some visual effects happening in the background but still it's about

00:01:00.720 --> 00:01:08.160
being in front or behind the camera. If you are a little bit more into the topic, you are probably

00:01:08.160 --> 00:01:15.519
aware that this is a really complex industry involving thousands of employees with a lot of

00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:23.279
studios, pre-production work, props creation, post-production and thousands of people involved.

00:01:24.959 --> 00:01:31.199
However, what I learned during working with this film studio and building this and other projects

00:01:31.199 --> 00:01:38.800
together is that the most important part in the moviemaking process is the data and reports.

00:01:39.199 --> 00:01:47.440
Here is just an example of a nearly 50 pages report that they are building manually every

00:01:47.440 --> 00:01:55.599
month but they used to be building before we joined them. So what is exactly our case with

00:01:55.599 --> 00:02:03.519
this film studio? They have over 20 departments, you know departments like creative, music,

00:02:04.400 --> 00:02:13.600
post-production, visual effects and they are working on around 300 productions. They are

00:02:13.600 --> 00:02:19.440
reporting and collecting data about around 300 productions at the same time that are on the

00:02:19.440 --> 00:02:25.839
different stages. So they might be just the ideas or they are already in production, different stages

00:02:25.839 --> 00:02:32.479
or they are released and they keep reporting about them. Some are even abandoned but they still need

00:02:32.559 --> 00:02:41.600
to see those in their reports. And they used to build around 60 manually generated reports

00:02:43.839 --> 00:02:49.520
mostly to coordinate the work between those departments so that one department knows that

00:02:49.520 --> 00:02:55.199
okay this is our time to take over the work and continue the process of moviemaking because the

00:02:55.199 --> 00:03:02.080
other department is ready with their work. Of course they were using some templates,

00:03:02.080 --> 00:03:06.559
we're using the previous version of the report but still this is a lot of work happening.

00:03:08.399 --> 00:03:16.000
That's fine, okay, moviemaking requires a lot of work but then in the end they are delivering us

00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:21.600
the great pieces of cinema. But the point is that no one was happy with the result.

00:03:21.600 --> 00:03:26.080
So with those reports that they put a lot of efforts, a lot of hours into this process,

00:03:26.080 --> 00:03:32.320
they were not satisfied with the process. And this is the moment when we joined them.

00:03:37.919 --> 00:03:40.479
And let me tell you a little bit more about the reasons

00:03:41.520 --> 00:03:44.639
behind this and how we helped them to solve them.

00:03:45.520 --> 00:03:51.199
So with these reports there was no single source of truth. So the data was coming from different

00:03:52.240 --> 00:04:00.080
databases, sources, and you could never be sure that what you are seeing is actually up to date

00:04:00.080 --> 00:04:08.160
and this is the latest value for a particular field in your report.

00:04:08.880 --> 00:04:18.640
There was no confidentiality and the reports were mostly shared via email and because it was a lot

00:04:18.640 --> 00:04:26.559
of manual work they kind of like tried to really put everything in a single report and shared it

00:04:26.559 --> 00:04:34.160
with everyone because that requires less working for them. However it wasn't a super efficient way

00:04:34.160 --> 00:04:41.519
to share sometimes sensitive data. For the same reason there was no customization of the content

00:04:42.160 --> 00:04:47.440
and people that were interested only in some productions they had to go through the whole

00:04:47.440 --> 00:04:54.160
report about everything to just find the information that is useful for them. Again of

00:04:54.160 --> 00:05:00.160
course they could create their reports for that particular production but one extra manual report

00:05:00.160 --> 00:05:06.079
to be added. And there was no clarity about those dependencies between the

00:05:07.040 --> 00:05:13.679
the departments. So if you are interested in changes for a particular production you need to

00:05:13.679 --> 00:05:20.000
open this email every month, find a report, 50 pages, find this information like okay nothing

00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:30.559
changed, I can wait more. Not super user-friendly way to learn about the updates.

00:05:33.200 --> 00:05:40.880
Okay so the tool that we created together with the film studio is called TARS and this is not an

00:05:40.880 --> 00:05:48.399
acronym. TARS is a robot from the interstellar movie that you might have seen. It's a complicated one, I

00:05:48.399 --> 00:05:55.679
don't understand the full plot but the robot was helping those astronauts to navigate, to do some

00:05:55.679 --> 00:06:02.079
heavy calculations during their travels. So this is quite accurate name for the tool that we delivered.

00:06:06.239 --> 00:06:13.440
So what exactly it is? Right now this is a single source of all film data for all those

00:06:13.440 --> 00:06:20.079
productions that are ongoing. So it's a single place that both people that are editing the data

00:06:20.079 --> 00:06:29.119
will go there and use a really nice front end to upload the changes.

00:06:30.799 --> 00:06:37.119
And for the data consumers this is a single place that they will come to get their data.

00:06:37.119 --> 00:06:42.320
Of course this is connecting different data sources but right now from the user perspective

00:06:42.320 --> 00:06:48.799
and for the report's perspective this is the only source of truth. This is also an automated report

00:06:48.799 --> 00:06:56.640
generation, a feature that is quite complex and I will tell you more about this also from the

00:06:56.640 --> 00:07:04.320
technical perspective how it operates. But right now all those manual reports and many more are

00:07:04.320 --> 00:07:11.600
automatically created with a given schedule and distributed for all the recipients interested.

00:07:13.279 --> 00:07:20.480
Also this is a tool that solves the access rights. So both on a level of the application, so there

00:07:20.480 --> 00:07:26.079
might be admins of the application and regular users as usual and this is like pretty simple.

00:07:26.079 --> 00:07:31.359
You can solve that with POSIT Connect groups for example. But this is also controlling the access

00:07:31.359 --> 00:07:38.239
to specific titles and even the fields so that people will, when they enter the TARS application,

00:07:39.119 --> 00:07:43.760
they only see the data that is relevant to them and nothing else.

00:07:46.000 --> 00:07:52.959
And this is truly a game changer for the film studio of how they are working with data and

00:07:52.959 --> 00:08:00.720
reports. So if there is any justice in this world the next Academy Awards should be something like that.

00:08:01.200 --> 00:08:02.720
But I'm not expecting that.

00:08:06.239 --> 00:08:11.679
But why would you care? I bet that not many of you are actually from the film industry.

00:08:14.720 --> 00:08:23.279
No one maybe. However those issues might sound really familiar with the data quality,

00:08:23.359 --> 00:08:33.599
managing access, efficient reporting and you probably face them in your organization as well.

00:08:35.119 --> 00:08:42.640
Just briefly searching, I found tons of reports about that. This is a really common problem

00:08:43.520 --> 00:08:51.440
but this is also what we spot at Appsilon. This is a really common case. Optimizing such processes

00:08:52.159 --> 00:08:53.840
is a usual case for our clients.

00:08:58.559 --> 00:09:02.960
I would love to tell you that you pick Shiny and this is the solution but of course it is

00:09:02.960 --> 00:09:09.679
not that simple. The project at this scale that is used across the whole organization

00:09:09.679 --> 00:09:16.479
with thousands of employees with multiple departments requires much more and the skills

00:09:17.200 --> 00:09:22.799
span across product ownership, design, software development of course.

00:09:24.559 --> 00:09:29.280
This might be a good moment for me to appreciate the whole team both on the Appsilon side

00:09:29.280 --> 00:09:30.960
and the client side for their great work.

00:09:35.440 --> 00:09:41.280
Shiny is a technology layer on top of all those skills required to deliver this project.

00:09:42.239 --> 00:09:48.000
And that might sound surprising during this conference but anything else could be used.

00:09:50.239 --> 00:09:59.520
For this case and for a tool that is modifying the processes on the corporate level like this,

00:09:59.520 --> 00:10:07.919
there is no strict requirement for actually Shiny or R to be used. That project could be

00:10:08.000 --> 00:10:13.520
done with any other technology. However, my point and my takeaway message for you

00:10:13.520 --> 00:10:18.960
and if there is only one thing that you will remember of this talk, I want you to remember

00:10:18.960 --> 00:10:28.080
this that Shiny can deliver such production ready tool. And it might even not come to your mind

00:10:28.080 --> 00:10:33.520
because usually it is considered and this is what I heard from my colleagues working with other

00:10:33.520 --> 00:10:42.000
technologies that this is some data scientists can play around with Shiny to build some simple

00:10:42.000 --> 00:10:51.119
tool to show their findings in a more interactive way. But what we are proving at Appsilon for years

00:10:51.119 --> 00:10:57.679
and with this is a perfect example that this can be actually a tool on the corporate level

00:10:58.559 --> 00:11:01.679
doing anything that is required by the business.

00:11:03.679 --> 00:11:12.159
OK, so now I would like to present you a little bit more solutions in TARS that are making this really

00:11:13.280 --> 00:11:21.280
useful for our client. This is complex, this is a long project with a lot of people involved

00:11:22.239 --> 00:11:28.719
and there are some solutions that I won't get a lot into the details both on the technical side

00:11:29.679 --> 00:11:37.039
and on the user experience side. Just recently we introduced this Confluence integration for example

00:11:37.039 --> 00:11:46.239
that allows our non-coding product owner to edit the help page using the editing tool in Confluence

00:11:46.239 --> 00:11:49.840
and this is automatically and directly reflected inside the Shiny application.

00:11:50.719 --> 00:11:59.520
Ask me later about those. What I would like to tell you more about today is this report generation

00:11:59.520 --> 00:12:01.200
that I called the TARS superpower.

00:12:03.919 --> 00:12:13.039
And to tell you how it works I will go step by step on the report creation process and will tell

00:12:13.599 --> 00:12:20.400
you details about its capabilities and how it was implemented using POSIT tools and Shiny

00:12:21.599 --> 00:12:29.119
capabilities. So first step is to select titles for your report and this is quite interesting

00:12:29.119 --> 00:12:35.359
because in the beginning you have this step that you can select either by filter criteria

00:12:35.359 --> 00:12:42.640
or specific titles. So if you are interested only in one production, let's say the new

00:12:42.640 --> 00:12:50.080
Batman movie, you are selecting specific titles and every week you can get updates on your

00:12:50.080 --> 00:12:58.400
Batman. However it is not the usual case. Most often our users are interested to select titles

00:12:58.400 --> 00:13:06.960
by the criteria. So for example they can pick that they are interested in the either like green

00:13:07.280 --> 00:13:16.799
so like approved titles or they can select abandoned titles and then the report automatically

00:13:16.799 --> 00:13:23.200
will select the titles for the report based on those criteria. So it might be the case that

00:13:23.200 --> 00:13:28.719
someone in the top management made a decision that the title is abandoned. They won't continue

00:13:28.719 --> 00:13:36.799
working on that and now with TARS as a report creation for abandoned titles you don't need to

00:13:36.799 --> 00:13:43.280
find this information through some different channels. It will be automatically included in

00:13:43.280 --> 00:13:52.640
your report for abandoned titles. Okay, so the second step is to configure your report and this

00:13:52.640 --> 00:14:03.039
is to select the fields that you will include. So as you might recall I said earlier that the big

00:14:03.039 --> 00:14:08.400
problem was that the reports are super general including all information sent to all the

00:14:08.400 --> 00:14:14.799
recipients. Now you can make your report very specific. Select only the fields from a department

00:14:14.799 --> 00:14:20.719
that you are interested in reporting for your selected titles. So the reports might be really

00:14:22.080 --> 00:14:24.880
covering only that you are interested.

00:14:25.840 --> 00:14:32.239
Okay and the first step and maybe the most important is automation of the report generation

00:14:32.239 --> 00:14:40.640
and scheduling. So how it works is that you can set your reports to be scheduled and you are picking

00:14:41.520 --> 00:14:48.239
how often it will be repeated and what is the start and end date. Similarly as you are setting

00:14:49.200 --> 00:15:01.599
the recurring event in the calendar. And with this schedule your reports will be generated and

00:15:01.599 --> 00:15:09.840
automatically distributed to your recipients. How it works in the technical perspective.

00:15:09.840 --> 00:15:14.479
I won't get very deep but for you to understand it better.

00:15:14.880 --> 00:15:23.679
There is an auxiliary tool called Scheduled Reports Generator. This is a fancy name for something

00:15:23.679 --> 00:15:33.919
that as you can see is an R Markdown report deployed to the Connect. And this report is

00:15:34.799 --> 00:15:44.719
is set to be repeated daily. And every day what it does it loops through the list of all

00:15:44.719 --> 00:15:49.840
saved reports and checks okay which report I should generate today.

00:15:51.840 --> 00:15:57.520
So this is like just output because this is not like a user-facing application auxiliary tool.

00:15:58.239 --> 00:16:07.760
And for the 25th of July it found four reports that should be generated that day according to

00:16:07.760 --> 00:16:16.080
what is the schedule of that report. Okay and what is happening for those reports.

00:16:17.280 --> 00:16:25.840
The data is snapshot as it is true on this particular day when they should be generated.

00:16:26.799 --> 00:16:33.039
The data both about which titles should be included if you are using filter criteria.

00:16:34.000 --> 00:16:40.960
And what is the state of your field values on this particular day.

00:16:42.000 --> 00:16:50.559
This data is snapshotted and saved on the other database. And this is the trick that

00:16:50.559 --> 00:16:56.559
the reports are not actually generated as a PDF or Excel files that will be really

00:16:56.559 --> 00:17:02.479
challenged to store. But we only snapshot the data that is required to generate those reports

00:17:02.479 --> 00:17:10.640
on the user demand. And from the user perspective the new report is added to their list of reports

00:17:10.640 --> 00:17:17.680
available in the TARS. And that one is generated by me so I have extra options. The other one is

00:17:17.920 --> 00:17:25.520
general that is shared by me as a recipient. So I can get this but I cannot edit, copy,

00:17:26.239 --> 00:17:31.839
or archive or even delete as I can with my POSIT.conf report. And there is also a download

00:17:31.839 --> 00:17:39.599
option. And this is the moment when the report is actually generated in the PDF form. And this

00:17:39.599 --> 00:17:45.280
is reaching out to your snapshot of the data that was true at the day when the report should be

00:17:45.280 --> 00:17:54.479
generated. And it does not matter that you are coming back after your vacation in two weeks and

00:17:54.479 --> 00:17:58.479
now you have no access to the data that was true at the moment when it should be.

00:18:00.719 --> 00:18:06.319
The old versions are of course archived and you have only the newest one available.

00:18:07.359 --> 00:18:12.479
Okay so this is a really powerful tool. The last step is that reports can be shared with

00:18:12.479 --> 00:18:18.079
the select recipients. Here for example I'm selecting my friend Agustin, leading developer

00:18:18.079 --> 00:18:25.439
in this project, to share the report as an editor. And he will see the same report available

00:18:25.439 --> 00:18:30.319
in his TARS and he will get email notification that the new version of report is read.

00:18:33.280 --> 00:18:40.000
Okay so to sum up, what is the current state? The TARS is used by hundreds of users

00:18:40.000 --> 00:18:47.199
to create custom reports to save hundreds of hours. And if next time you go to cinema, the

00:18:47.199 --> 00:18:52.000
movie will be actually created using the TARS if this is coming from that film studio.

00:18:53.599 --> 00:18:59.359
And the thing that I wanted you to remember is that the corporate level processes can be

00:18:59.359 --> 00:19:05.119
optimized with Shiny. There are no limits here when it comes to build a really production level software.

00:19:05.760 --> 00:19:09.839
Thank you very much. You can find me here or near the Absalon booth

00:19:10.400 --> 00:19:12.959
and I will be happy to answer any questions. Thank you.

00:19:18.160 --> 00:19:24.400
All right so we're actually right on time. So I guess the only quick question I have for you is

00:19:25.280 --> 00:19:28.400
did you meet any famous movie stars while working on this project?

00:19:29.119 --> 00:19:35.680
No, but right after the conference I'm actually going to Los Angeles,

00:19:35.680 --> 00:19:39.920
so I hope I will meet some during this visit.

